    <text>
        <body>       
                 
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Washington D. C. January 25<hi rend="sup">th</hi><lb/>
                1888.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Dr. S. Morais<lb/>
                546. n. fifth Str.<lb/></p>
            <p>Philadelphia.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear friend&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>I cannot forbear to tell you<lb/> of a <hi rend="underline">nice literarical finding at auction</hi><lb/> some weeks ago.  I know what a great<lb/> admirer of the Luzzato&#39;s you are.<lb/>  Are you possessed of&#44; or have you ever<lb/> seen the &#91;Hebrew&#93; of &#91;Hebrew&#93; the son of<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; a &#91;Hebrew&#93; to the &#91;Hebrew&#93; Tesayah Basan<lb/> of &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; printed in Mantua &#91;Hebrew&#93; cum<lb/> licenza de Superiori&#63;  I was so fortunate<lb/> to get it.  It is some thing grand in style&#44;<lb/> itself&#44; whilst it is teaching <hi rend="underline">style</hi> or<lb/> <hi rend="underline">rhetorik</hi> in a manner&#44; which would<lb/> create the admiration of the <hi rend="underline">gentiles</hi><lb/> as well as that of the <hi rend="underline">despisers</hi> of the<lb/> old <hi rend="underline">hebrew mother</hi>&#34; among her own children<lb/> if &#34;we should translate it into <hi rend="underline">english</hi>&#34;<lb/> &#38; <hi rend="underline">german</hi>&#44; accompanied by the <hi rend="underline">Hebrew</hi><lb/> text.  If you are desirous to see the book&#44;<lb/> I will allow it to you for only a few<lb/> weeks&#44; and I tell you before hand&#44; that<lb/> I lay a <hi rend="underline">caveat</hi> upon its <hi rend="underline">republication</hi> in <hi rend="underline">translation</hi>.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Yet&#44; if you are desirous&#44; to have a hand<lb/> in it&#44; I offer you <hi rend="underline">partnership</hi>&#44; for<lb/> I know&#44; without flattery the work would<lb/> be enhanced by your cooperation.<lb/></p>
            <p>Concerning my <hi rend="underline">Mailand</hi> &#40;Italy&#41;<lb/> obligation&#44; of the year 1855&#44; which I hold<lb/> since more than 17 years&#44; I have not<lb/> dared a step <hi rend="underline">as yet</hi>&#44; to find out whether<lb/> it is drawn or not&#33;  However&#44; I shall<lb/> write this week to a New&#45;York Banker<lb/> who deals in these paper to get some<lb/> information according to the result<lb/> I shall take liberty again to write to you<lb/> to be so kind and translate a letter<lb/> of mine to the magistrate of Mailand.<lb/></p>
            <p>Hoping this will reach you &#38;<lb/> worthy family all in the best of<lb/> health &#38; conditions I remain<lb/> Yours<lb/> truly<lb/> Rev. Isaac Stemple<lb/></p>
            <p>P. S. I am since July<lb/> last here out of office&#59;<lb/> and hope to obtain soon<lb/> another place.  This sort of so <hi rend="underline">called orthodox</hi><lb/> congregations <hi rend="underline">cause us</hi> to be for ever &#91;Hebrew&#93;.&#45;&#45;<lb/> I got<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>also at the same time recently a hebrew<lb/> <hi rend="underline">outline</hi> of the <hi rend="underline">life</hi> &#38; <hi rend="underline">works</hi> of Moses<lb/> Mendelsohn&#44; the Philosopher&#59; also in<lb/> a beautiful hebrew style. a rare work<lb/> without <sic>titelpage</sic>. but I think it<lb/> is a part of the &#91;Hebrew&#93; of the end<lb/> of last century.&#45;&#45;<lb/></p>
            </body>
